It's a bit confusing because we've named the network attachment definitions as net1, net2, net3, etc.  However, in the container the interfaces are named by default as net${X} where X corresponds to the number of the device.  For example, if you've added one device using the net2 attachment definition, it will be named net1 in the container.  If you've added two devices using the net2, net3 network attachment definitions, they will be named net1, net2 in the container.

It is possible to rename the devices to whatever you want by specifying the 'interface' in the pod's network annotation dict.

For example, if you wanted the device associated with the 'net2' network attachment definition in the example above to be named 'sriov0', you would change the

                k8s.v1.cni.cncf.io/networks: '[
                    { "name": "net2" }
                ]'

To look like:

                k8s.v1.cni.cncf.io/networks: '[
                    { "name": "net2", "interface": "sriov0" }
                ]'

Then you could say something like:

After creating the pod, the interface ``sriov0`` which uses one |SRIOV| |VF| will appear in the associated container\(s\).

The same could be done to the other SR-IOV examples we have.

